    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_728394310" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/728394310" />
    <a title="Mark Carolla" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/24256133-mark-carolla"><img alt="Mark Carolla" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1380210945p2/24256133.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/728394310?book_show_action=true">Sep 26, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Mark Carolla" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Mark Carolla" href="/user/show/24256133-mark-carolla">Mark Carolla</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer728394310" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4382089957150683191">This novel is James Bruno&apos;s best work so far. It is a step above his last outstanding work &quot;Tribe&quot; and a quantum leap beyond his earlier Amazon Best Sellers, &quot;Permanent Interests&quot; and &quot;Chasm.&quot; But don&apos;t take it only from me; this novel has received wide acclaim and favorable reviews in the Miami Cuban press and community; James has been interviewed on Sirius Radio Christina and featured in other Latin American press reviews. He has apparently bounded across the literary moat from analytical dipl</span>
  <span id="freeText4382089957150683191" style="display:none">This novel is James Bruno's best work so far. It is a step above his last outstanding work "Tribe" and a quantum leap beyond his earlier Amazon Best Sellers, "Permanent Interests" and "Chasm." But don't take it only from me; this novel has received wide acclaim and favorable reviews in the Miami Cuban press and community; James has been interviewed on Sirius Radio Christina and featured in other Latin American press reviews. He has apparently bounded across the literary moat from analytical diplomatic reporting to entertaining yet realistic fiction. My fiction reading goal is to be entertained, realistically so, and not to be enmeshed in deep literary tomes like Garcia Marquez (even though I enjoy him.) I'm more into Michener and Wouk. So, my review is based more on this work's authenticity and verisimilitude than on style. I also have served as a Cuban and Latin American specialist in several US defense Department Agencies and like my thrillers to reflect the realities of culture, geography, military order of battle and the intelligence professions. I can't get five pages into a Robert Ludlum or Brad Thor novel, for example, because those authors don't write about the real world of intelligence tradecraft as I knew it. In my opinion, James is in the same league with Dan Silva and Frederick Forsyth and to a certain degree John Le Carre. James was one of the few US Diplomats with experience across the island of Cuba and is certainly an "Old Cuban Hand." What makes James stand out is that he does meticulous research on the locales he hasn't visited; and his knowledge of unclassified military and security force structure, order-of-battle and tactics is exceptional. He weaves realistic intelligence and counterintelligence tradecraft as best as can pass the necessary negotiated security reviews into his novel. There are also dark secrets and suspenseful plot turns throughout. As in his earlier novels his career field experience, graduate study at the US Naval War College and broad yet comprehensive knowledge of the US National Security establishment is deployed throughout the telling of his stories. I find this work to be totally realistic despite IC and State Department "review" and redaction (polite terms for "censorship" that those of us who worked with Top Secret clearances are bound to when publishing a work like this. ) As a former analyst and Defense Diplomat I relished the thoughts of "I know that pompous ass;" or "I did that" and "I've been in that meeting" as I read this page-turner. The only real gripe that I have is that James describes a Cuban Railways diesel as "chugging," which most rail fans like me would rather apply to steam locomotives. However, the ill-maintained and old second hand diesels (other than the new Chinese models) in Cuba probably do make a rattling chugging sound. Despite his disclaimers, I recognize under different names many of the heroes, villains, dedicated professionals, patriots, grovelling butt-kissing ticket punchers, stupid bureaucrats, traitors, quiet analysts, law enforcement officers, jerks and scumbags that James - and I - either proudly worked with, in spite of or against. The plot is a real suspenseful page turner; and as one of the few US diplomats who has traveled all over Cuba his text captures the music, the moods, the language, the culture and the day-to-day life of the wonderful Cuban people. It is not a right-wing polemic against the Revolution; but does paint the Cuban scene as the Cuban people see it. It certainly will not be well-received by the dictators Raul and Fidel; in Caracas; other places in Latin America that seek to emulate the disastrous Cuban model of dictatorship; nor by domestic apologists or romanticized political theorists for the Castro Brothers' dictatorship. I have to give it Five Stars....and would recommend it for university courses on Cuba or the Intelligence Community. </span>
  <a data-text-id="4382089957150683191" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


