<div id="review_708944127" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/708944127" />
    <a title="Dan Santos" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/22003812-dan-santos"><img alt="Dan Santos" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1493421822p2/22003812.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/708944127?book_show_action=true">Sep 01, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Dan Santos" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Dan Santos" href="/user/show/22003812-dan-santos">Dan Santos</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer708944127" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16389085565202932151">OK, Bruno, where&apos;s the sequel? Nick Castillo is the new hero in town. What&apos;s he going to do next?<br/><br/>This book takes you spiritually out of your environment and places you in a spot so foreign and distinctive that you are compelled to enjoy yourself; the mark of a great writer. He&apos;s very imaginative when it comes to character development. There is just enough detail about the good guys and the bad guys. He has the right formula to make the reader imagine the rest, rather than overfeed his imaginatio</span>
  <span id="freeText16389085565202932151" style="display:none">OK, Bruno, where's the sequel? Nick Castillo is the new hero in town. What's he going to do next?<br /><br />This book takes you spiritually out of your environment and places you in a spot so foreign and distinctive that you are compelled to enjoy yourself; the mark of a great writer. He's very imaginative when it comes to character development. There is just enough detail about the good guys and the bad guys. He has the right formula to make the reader imagine the rest, rather than overfeed his imagination. The story is innovative and timely. The book is technically perfect.<br /><br />James Bruno, more than any other person I know has the credentials to talk about today's and tomorrow's Cuba. And he does, in a masterfully written thriller that keeps you on the edge of your seat. I can imagine how he pulled teeth at State to get this story approved for publication. It's so real!<br /><br />My finger hovered over the fifth star for a long moment. While I suspect his motivation was to prepare us for the sequel, the ending is somewhat short of what I personally expected; but then, I'm not a stranger to Cuban affairs. It may be unfair of me not to fork out that fifth star, but I've decided to admit that my thirst for more may have been the reason.</span>
  <a data-text-id="16389085565202932151" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


