<div id="review_712076276" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/712076276" />
    <a title="Michael O&#39;Gara" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/7123891-michael-o-gara"><img alt="Michael O&#39;Gara" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1442612105p2/7123891.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/712076276?book_show_action=true">Sep 05, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Michael O&#39;Gara" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Michael O&#39;Gara" href="/user/show/7123891-michael-o-gara">Michael O&#39;Gara</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer712076276" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13012483435022328125">Intrigue, assassination, espionage, politics, and civil war are some of the components that make the thriller Havana Queen an entertaining read.<br/> <br/>Havana Queen deals with fictional events surrounding the approaching end of the Castro regime. The story deals with conflicts within the Cuban government as senior Cuban officials jockey to assume control and how that affects U.S. interests, Cuban exiles and the Cuban people. I found it to be an entertaining read. The book’s strength is the author’s dep</span>
  <span id="freeText13012483435022328125" style="display:none">Intrigue, assassination, espionage, politics, and civil war are some of the components that make the thriller Havana Queen an entertaining read.<br /> <br />Havana Queen deals with fictional events surrounding the approaching end of the Castro regime. The story deals with conflicts within the Cuban government as senior Cuban officials jockey to assume control and how that affects U.S. interests, Cuban exiles and the Cuban people. I found it to be an entertaining read. The book’s strength is the author’s depiction of Cuban society and weaving that into the book’s plot.<br /><br />It was the author’s ability to convey a realistic and interesting look into a country most of us know little about that carried me through the first chapters. The book is unusually structured as the first third of the book is mainly back-story. I found myself a little distracted when after several chapters I realized I had not identified the main character. I wondered if I had missed something. Still it was good reading so I kept on.<br /><br />The things I liked most about the book is what seems to be a realistic look into a decaying Cuban political system, the daily life and psyche of the people, as well as some interesting fictional characters and an interesting story line. I found the sexual obsession of the Cuban spymaster to be a distraction and stretched believability. It almost seemed an excuse to add a little unnecessary erotica to the book.<br /> <br />All in all, this is an enjoyable read.<br /> <br />Note: The author provided me with a review copy so I could do an honest review.<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="13012483435022328125" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


